Author: jl777c#5810
Content: yes, the fact is someone that doesnt understand ssh and user accounts for unix, shouldnt complain about our support, they should be reading "ssh for newbies" and things like that. we cant be expected to have everything work for everyone, regardless of their knowledge. it is assumed that basic unix is known by someone in a project trying to launch a new chain

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: the alternative is to fork some other coin, make source code changes correctly and then do all the runtime fork stuff that is needed

Author: SHossain#0007
Content: It seems he wants to run without learning how to stand first and walk

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: https://linuxacademy.com/ just 50 bucks per month

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: i think to refer to service providers if they dont have the required skills. it is just "running with scissors" to have people not able to do very basic command line trying to launch assetchains

Author: SHossain#0007
Content: and complaing that road isn't smooth for him

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: maybe we can make some page with helpful links for someone without any unix experience so they can at least know what they need to know. any competent advanced user from any os, would be able to learn what is needed, given the study materials

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but if you notice a distinct lack of understanding,just keep referring to the newbie study materials. only after they are able to know up from down in the ssh world, should they even attempt to start assetchains. after all it is just a matter to launch komodod with the right set of parameters on two different nodes. if that is beyond someone, then no amount of support will suffice and only lead to complaints about bad support. so we shouldnt even try to support people without the skills to launch assetchains. they need to use service providers or learn first.

Author: TonyL#3577
Content:
I recommend to look into LPIC preparation courses - it's a fastest way to play a little with both Debian and RHEL and understand what's going on if not using it in everyday life. There is a little of everything in one place so it's easy for kick-off. 
And usually in such courses study how to use `man` what's is the most important üòÉ

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: And would be cool to pass this computer science course in parallel in my opinion :trollface: : https://www.edx.org/course/cs50s-introduction-computer-science-harvardx-cs50x There is C using for explanation/labs so it's giving more points for diving into komodo. And it's free!
